      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CI Workflow for Monthly Capacity Tests"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "yaml"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# .github/workflows/capacity-test.yml\nname: Monthly Capacity Test\n\non:\n  schedule:\n    - cron: '0 2 1 * *'   # 02:00 UTC on the 1st of each month\n  workflow_dispatch:\n    inputs:\n      sla_p99_ms:\n        description: 'SLA p99 threshold in ms'\n        default: '6000'\n\njobs:\n  capacity-test:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    timeout-minutes: 120\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-python@v5\n        with: {python-version: '3.12'}\n      - run: pip install locust fastapi uvicorn pyyaml\n\n      - name: Start mock Claude API\n        run: uvicorn tests.capacity.mock_server:app --port 8001 &\n\n      - name: Start Claude service\n        run: |\n          CLAUDE_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8001 \\\n          uvicorn app:app --port 8000 --workers 4 &\n          sleep 3\n\n      - name: Run staircase capacity test\n        run: |\n          locust -f tests/capacity/staircase_locustfile.py \\\n            --headless \\\n            --host http://localhost:8000 \\\n            --csv /tmp/capacity \\\n            --html /tmp/capacity_report.html\n\n      - name: Generate capacity report\n        run: |\n          python tests/capacity/generate_report.py \\\n            /tmp/capacity_stats_history.csv \\\n            --sla-p99-ms ${{ inputs.sla_p99_ms || '6000' }} \\\n            --output /tmp/capacity_report.json\n\n      - name: Format and display report\n        run: python tests/capacity/markdown_report.py /tmp/capacity_report.json\n\n      - name: Check headroom threshold\n        run: |\n          python - <<'EOF'\n          import json, sys\n          r = json.load(open(\"/tmp/capacity_report.json\"))\n          headroom = r.get(\"headroom_pct\")\n          if headroom is None:\n            print(\"No saturation found \u2014 system is well within capacity.\")\n            sys.exit(0)\n          if headroom < 10:\n            print(f\"CRITICAL: Only {headroom:.0f}% headroom remaining!\")\n            sys.exit(1)\n          print(f\"Headroom: {headroom:.0f}% \u2014 within acceptable range.\")\n          EOF\n\n      - name: Upload artifacts\n        if: always()\n        uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4\n        with:\n          name: capacity-test-${{ github.run_id }}\n          path: |\n            /tmp/capacity_report.json\n            /tmp/capacity_report.html\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tracking Capacity Over Releases"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Commit each month's capacity report to a dedicated directory. This creates a historical record that shows whether headroom is shrinking (indicating traffic growth outpacing capacity) or stable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# After each capacity test run, archive the report:\nMONTH=$(date +%Y-%m)\ncp /tmp/capacity_report.json capacity-reports/${MONTH}.json\ngit add capacity-reports/${MONTH}.json\ngit commit -m \"capacity: monthly report ${MONTH}\"\ngit push\n\n# Compare to previous month:\nPREV_MONTH=$(date -d '1 month ago' +%Y-%m)\npython - <<'EOF'\nimport json\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\ncurr = json.loads(Path(f\"capacity-reports/{MONTH}.json\").read_text())\nprev_path = Path(f\"capacity-reports/{PREV_MONTH}.json\")\nif not prev_path.exists():\n    print(\"No previous month to compare.\")\nelse:\n    prev = json.loads(prev_path.read_text())\n    curr_h = curr.get(\"headroom_pct\", 0)\n    prev_h = prev.get(\"headroom_pct\", 0)\n    delta = curr_h - prev_h\n    trend = \"\u25b2\" if delta > 0 else (\"\u25bc\" if delta < 0 else \"\u2192\")\n    print(f\"Headroom: {prev_h:.0f}% \u2192 {curr_h:.0f}% ({trend} {abs(delta):.0f}%)\")\nEOF\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Breaks First Under Capacity Pressure"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In Claude API integrations, the saturation pattern is predictable. Understanding the failure cascade helps you plan mitigations before running the capacity test."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Connection pool exhaustion \u2014 your HTTP client runs out of keep-alive connections; new requests queue or fail fast."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Rate limit cascade \u2014 Anthropic 429s increase, retry storms amplify load, latency spikes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Worker starvation \u2014 async event loop threads block on I/O while waiting for model responses."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Memory pressure \u2014 streaming response buffers accumulate when consumers can't drain them fast enough."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Timeout waterfall \u2014 downstream timeouts start hitting as p99 crosses user-configured timeout values."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The most common Claude integration failure mode is retry storm amplification: high load \u2192 429 rate limits \u2192 retries \u2192 more load \u2192 more 429s \u2192 exponential queue growth. Add jitter to your retry backoff and set a maximum retry budget to break this cycle."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Capacity test automation finds the saturation point by running a staircase ramp to failure, computing headroom against the expected peak, and producing a structured report. Run monthly, track headroom over time, and alert when headroom falls below 10%. The staircase pattern gives a clean latency-vs-concurrency curve that clearly shows the knee point and the specific VU count where the system crosses its SLA threshold \u2014 giving the operations team a precise number for auto-scaling triggers and traffic throttle limits."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
